DAY 4: File Operations

  Creating, Copying, Moving, and Deleting Files


## Commands

  1.  touch – Create Empty Files / Update Timestamps
  2.  cp – Copy Files and Directories
  3.  mv – Move/Rename Files and Directories
  4.  find – Search for Files
  5.  locate – Fast File Search (using database)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Rename a file
$ mv oldname. txt newname. txt
    
# Move file to directory
$ mv file. txt /home / raman / Documents /
    
# Move multiple files
$ mv file1 . txt file2 . txt file3 . txt/backup/
    
# Rename a directory
$ mv old_folder new_folder
    
# Move with verbose
$ mv -v file. txt / tmp /
renamed ’ file. txt ’ -> ’/ tmp / file. txt ’
    
# Interactive mode
$ mv -i file. txt existing. txt
mv: overwrite ’ existing. txt ’? y
    
# Don’t overwrite
$ mv -n file. txt existing. txt
    
# ( existing . txt is not overwritten )
# Backup before overwrite
$ mv -b file. txt existing. txt
    
# Move using wildcards
$ mv *. log / var/log/archive/

# Remove single file
$ rm file. txt
    
# Remove multiple files
$ rm file1 . txt file2 . txt file3 . txt
    
# Remove with confirmation
$ rm -i important_file. txt

rm: remove regular file ’ important_file. txt ’? y

    
# Remove directory and contents
$ rm -r folder /
$ rm - rf folder / # Force , no prompts
    
# Verbose removal
$ rm - rv project /
removed ’ project / file1. txt ’
removed ’ project / file2. txt ’
removed directory ’ project / ’

    
# Remove files matching pattern
$ rm *. tmp
$ rm *. log

    
# Remove empty directory
$ rm -d empty_folder /
    
# Safe recursive delete ( prompt once )
$ rm - rI large_folder /
rm: remove 1 argument recursively? y

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  
DANGER: Be extremely careful with rm -rf!
# NEVER run these commands :
$ rm - rf / # Deletes ENTIRE system
$ rm - rf / * # Deletes everything
$ rm - rf ~ # Deletes your home directory
$ rm - rf. # Deletes current directory
# ALWAYS double - check before using rm - rf !
Best Practice: Use rm -ri for important deletions (interactive mode).


  # Find by name
$ find/home - name "*. txt "
$ find. - name " config. yml "
$ find / - iname " readme *" # Case - insensitive
# Find by type
$ find / var - type f - name "*. log "
$ find / etc - type d - name " ssh "
# Find by size
$ find / - size +100 M # Larger than 100 MB
$ find /home - size -1 k # Smaller than 1 KB
$ find. - size +10 M - size -50 M # Between 10 -50 MB
# Find by time
$ find /var/log - mtime -7 # Modified in last 7 days
$ find . - mtime +30 # Modified more than 30 days ago
$ find . - mmin -60 # Modified in last 60 minutes
# Find by owner
$ find / home - user raman
$ find / var - group www - data
# Find by permissions
$ find / - perm 777
$ find / home - perm -u = w # User has write permission
# Find empty files/directories
$ find . - empty
$ find . - type f - empty
$ find . - type d - empty
# Limit search depth
$ find . - maxdepth 2 - name "*. txt "
# Execute command on results
$ find . - name "*. tmp " - exec rm {} \;
$ find . - name "*. log " - exec mv {} / backup / \;
$ find . - type f - exec chmod 644 {} \;
# Combined conditions
$ find / var - type f - name "*. log " - size +10 M - mtime +7


# Update database first ( run as root )
  
$ sudo updatedb
# Basic search
$ locate passwd
/ etc / passwd
/ etc / passwd -
/ usr / share/doc / passwd / ...
# Case - insensitive
$ locate -i README
# Limit results
$ locate -n 5 "*. conf "
# Count matches
$ locate -c "*. log "
1523
# Basename only
$ locate -b passwd

find vs locate:
• find – Real-time search, slower but always current
• locate – Uses a database, very fast, but may be outdated
• Run sudo updatedb to update the locate database


  Option Description
-name "pattern" Search by filename (case-sensitive)
-iname "pattern" Search by name (case-insensitive)
-type f Find only files
-type d Find only directories
-type l Find only symbolic links
-size +10M Find files larger than 10MB
-size -10M Find files smaller than 10MB
-mtime -7 Modified in the last 7 days
-mtime +30 Modified more than 30 days ago
-user username Files owned by user
-perm 644 Files with specific permissions
-empty Find empty files/directories
-maxdepth n Limit search depth
-exec cmd {} \; Execute command on results


